       <h1 class="art-title"> Laravel 5 Chess Captcha Form Authentication </h1> 
       <div class="art-meta"> 
        <span class="art-date"><i class="fa fa-calendar-o"></i> July 15 2016</span> • 
        <a href="/blog/category/tutorials" class="art-category"><i class="fa fa-folder"></i> Tutorials</a> • 
        <span class="art-readtime"><i class="fa fa-book"></i> 5 min read</span> 
       </div> 
      </div> 
     </div> 
    </div> 
   </section> 
   <div class="container"> 
    <div class="row"> 
     <div class="col-lg-8 col-md-8 col-xs-12"> 
      <div> 
       <article> 
        <p class="art-fulltext"></p>
        <p>Chesscaptcha is a captcha system inspired by chess. The nice thing about this implementation is that it can also be used by non-chess players and that's because the default mode requires copying a given position on the input board, something that can be done by anyone. There is also the mate in one mode where the visitor has to be a chess player of course. We are happy that the developer of the project is a member of our team here at emar.</p>
        <p>In this tutorial we'll be dealing with the installation of chesscaptcha in laravel and its use on an example registration form. Let's get started.</p>
        <h3>1. INSTALL WITH COMPOSER</h3>
        <p>In your terminal type the following:</p>
        <pre>composer require elioair/chesscaptcha</pre>
        <p>This will download the package in the vendor directory of your laravel project.</p>
        <h3>2. FILE ARRANGEMENT</h3>
        <p>Since this is a composite package meaning that it has both a php and a javascript side we have to move the required js files from the package's directory into the public directory. So in our case this will be done by moving the chesscaptcha.js (or the chesscaptcha.min.js) file from <b>vendor/elioair/chesscaptcha/assets/js</b> to the <b>public/js</b> folder.</p>
        <p>Next we'll have to move - or copy if you don't care about duplicate files - the pieces folder under <b>assets/img</b> to the <b>public/img/</b> folder. This is done because the javascript part won't be able to access image files that reside outside the public folder.</p>
        <p>Lastly we'll have to set the path in the BoardImageCreator.php class file. So go in <b>vendor/elioair/chesscaptcha/src/BoardImageCreator.php</b> and in line 24 change the path to the one of your installation. In my case that was:</p>
        <pre>protected $pieceImageDir = "/var/www/mylaravelproject.dev/public/img/pieces/";</pre>
        <h3>3. CREATE A FORM VIEW</h3>
        <p>We'll be using the default authentication controller that is built-in into Laravel so our form template will have to be created in a file structure specified by this. Let's create now the auth directory under <b>resources/views</b> and in this directory create the file <b>register.blade.php</b> that will hold the registration form and paste this in it:<span style="line-height: 1.42857;">Open the routes.php file and paste these in.</span></p>
        <pre>@if (count($errors) &gt; 0)<br>	    &lt;div class="alert alert-danger"&gt;<br>	        &lt;strong&gt;Whoops!&lt;/strong&gt; There were some problems with your input.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;<br>	        &lt;ul&gt;<br>	            @foreach ($errors-&gt;all() as $error)<br>	                &lt;li&gt;{{ $error }}&lt;/li&gt;<br>	            @endforeach<br>	        &lt;/ul&gt;<br>	    &lt;/div&gt;<br>	@endif<br>	&lt;h1&gt;Register&lt;/h1&gt;<br>	&lt;form method="POST" action="/auth/register"&gt;<br>	  &lt;div class="form-group"&gt;<br>	    &lt;label for="name"&gt;Name&lt;/label&gt;<br>	    &lt;input type="text" class="form-control" id="name" name="name" placeholder="Name"&gt;<br>	  &lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;div class="form-group"&gt;<br>	    &lt;label for="email"&gt;Email address&lt;/label&gt;<br>	    &lt;input type="email" class="form-control" id="email" name="email" placeholder="Email"&gt;<br>	  &lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;div class="form-group"&gt;<br>	    &lt;label for="password"&gt;Password&lt;/label&gt;<br>	    &lt;input type="password" class="form-control" id="password" name="password" placeholder="Password"&gt;<br>	  &lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;div class="form-group"&gt;<br>	    &lt;label for="password_conf"&gt;Confirm Password&lt;/label&gt;<br>	    &lt;input type="password" class="form-control" id="password_conf" name="password_confirmation" placeholder="Retype Password"&gt;<br>	  &lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;div class="checkbox"&gt;<br>	    &lt;label&gt;<br>	      &lt;input type="checkbox"&gt; I accept the terms<br>	    &lt;/label&gt;<br>	  &lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;!-- The #chesscaptcha div where the captcha will be rendered. If needed you can change the # in the $config array --&gt;<br>	  &lt;div id="chesscaptcha"&gt;&lt;?php if($config['nojsfallback'] == 'yes'){ echo $chesscaptcha-&gt;noJsHtml($config['pieceImages']);}?&gt;&lt;/div&gt;<br>	  &lt;input type="hidden" name="_token" value="{{ csrf_token() }}"&gt;<br>	  &lt;button type="submit" id="submitform" class="btn btn-default"&gt;Register&lt;/button&gt;<br>	&lt;/form&gt;<br>	.....<br>	&lt;script src="/js/jquery.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;<br>    &lt;!-- Bootstrap Core JavaScript --&gt;<br>    &lt;script src="/js/bootstrap.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>
        <p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.1;"><br></span></p>
        <p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.1;">4. CREATE THE ROUTES</span></p>
        <p>Open the <b>routes.php</b> file and paste these in.</p>
        <pre>Route::get('auth/register', 'Auth\AuthController@getRegister');<br>Route::post('auth/register', 'Auth\AuthController@postRegister');</pre>
        <h3>5. CHESSCAPTCHA CONFIGURATION</h3>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p>It is time now to configure the captcha system. In the beginning of the register.blade.php file put the following:</p>
        <pre>
         <!--?php<br-->  // The array that contains the configuration for the php side<br>  $config = [<br>    'divId'=&gt;'chesscaptcha',<br>    'whitesquare'=&gt;'#f0d9b5',<br>    'blacksquare'=&gt;'#b58863',<br>    'matemode'=&gt;'no', // yes or no<br>    'nojsfallback'=&gt;'no', // yes or no; activate the fallback in case js is disabled<br>    'titleoverride'=&gt;'Copy the position below', // text override<br>    'titlemateoverride'=&gt;'Mate-In-One', // text override<br>    'helpoverride'=&gt;'Drag the pieces into the board to copy the given position. To remove a piece drag it out of the board.', // text override<br>    'startoverride'=&gt;'Start', // text override<br>    'clearoverride'=&gt;'Clear', // text override<br>    'pieceStyle'=&gt;'wikipedia', // the name of the piece style to use or 'random', default is 'wikipedia'<br>  ];<br>    $chesscaptcha = new \Elioair\ChessCaptcha\ChessCaptcha($config['whitesquare'], $config['blacksquare'], $config['matemode'], $config['nojsfallback'], $config['pieceStyle']);<br>  ?&gt;</pre>
        <p>and this near the end of the file after the jquery script request line. This is the configuration for the javascript part so you'll have to set the <b>cc_pathtoimg</b> parameter to the location of the piece images.</p>
        <pre>&lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;<br>    // The object containing the configuration for the js side<br>    var chessCaptchaParams = {<br>        cc_divId: '&lt;?php echo $config['divId'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_mateMode: '&lt;?php echo $config['matemode']?&gt;' === 'no' ? false : true,<br>        cc_whiteSquare: '&lt;?php echo $config['whitesquare'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_blackSquare: '&lt;?php echo $config['blacksquare'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_titleOverride: '&lt;?php echo $config['titleoverride'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_mateTitleOverride: '&lt;?php echo $config['titlemateoverride'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_helpOverride: '&lt;?php echo $config['helpoverride'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_startOverride: '&lt;?php echo $config['startoverride'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_clearOverride: '&lt;?php echo $config['clearoverride'];?&gt;',<br>        cc_sideToPlay: '&lt;?php echo $chesscaptcha-&gt;chessCaptchaFenCode[2]; ?&gt;',<br>        cc_challenge: '&lt;?php echo $chesscaptcha-&gt;chessCaptchaChallenge; ?&gt;',  // The image of the position<br>        cc_matechallenge: '&lt;?php echo $chesscaptcha-&gt;chessCaptchaFenCode[0];?&gt;',  // The fen code of matemode position<br>        cc_pathtoimg: '/img/pieces',<br>        cc_piecestyle: '&lt;?php echo $chesscaptcha-&gt;chessCaptchaPieceStyle;?&gt;',<br>    };<br>    &lt;/script&gt;<br>    &lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/js/chesscaptcha.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>
        <p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">The complete </span><b style="line-height: 1.42857;">register.blade.php</b><span style="line-height: 1.42857;"> code can be found in this <a href="https://gist.github.com/elioair/c9a18b084f666b3ae7a5">Gist</a>.</span></p>
        <p>Now if you visit <b class="">/auth/register</b> in your browser you should see the form with the chesscaptcha in it.</p>
        <p class=""><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><br></p>
        <h3>6. VALIDATION OF THE INPUT DATA.</h3>
        <p>In this last step we'll validate the input data against the captcha challenge. We'll do it by editing the default authentication controller <b>Controllers/Auth/AuthController.php</b> and modifying the validator method. Also note that Laravel by default redirects to /home when the user is logged-in successfully and since we don't have such a route it is a good idea to add the <b>private</b> <b>$redirectTo = '/';</b> right below use <b>AuthenticatesAndRegistersUsers</b>, <b>ThrottlesLogins;</b> inside the <b>AuthController</b> class. Next we'll have to add the custom validation rule by extending Validator and add some custom error messages - inline in this case - for the captcha input. So the modified validator method will look like this:</p>
        <pre class="">protected function validator(array $data)<br>{<br>    // Extend the Validator to check also for the chesscaptcha<br>    Validator::extend('chesscaptcha', function($attribute, $value, $parameters)<br>    {<br>        $noJs = false;  // No disabled-javascript fallback<br>        $colorTolerance = false; // Config param: Change this to true if you want to enable color tolerance<br>        $validate = \Elioair\ChessCaptcha\ChessCaptcha::validate($value, $noJs, $colorTolerance);<br>        return $validate;<br>    });<br>    return Validator::make($data, [<br>        'name' =&gt; 'required|max:255',<br>        'email' =&gt; 'required|email|max:255|unique:users',<br>        'password' =&gt; 'required|confirmed|min:6',<br>        'chesscaptchaposition' =&gt; 'required|chesscaptcha',<br>    ],<br>    $messages = [<br>        'chesscaptchaposition.required' =&gt; 'Empty chesscaptcha.',<br>        'chesscaptcha' =&gt; 'Wrong chesscaptcha.',<br>    ]);<br>}</pre>
        <p> </p>
        <p> </p>
        <p class=""><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><br></p>
        <h3>CONCLUSION</h3>
        <p>Although it might seem like a lot of work it is really easy to incorporate chess captcha to your websites' forms. As a system it is useful not only to avoid spammers when used as an alternative to distorted characters in regular mode but also to avoid, when set to mate-in-one mode, non-chess players accessing your site.</p>
        <p class=""><a href="https://twitter.com/elioair">&nbsp;FOLLOW ELIOAIR</a>&nbsp; | <a href="https://github.com/elioair/chesscaptcha">PROJECT ON GITHUB</a><br></p>
        <p></p>
